04000nam a22006015i 9781575066417DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750664177 a10.1515/97815750664172doi  a(DE-B1597)606815  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a224/.206091 aMoon, Joshua N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJeremiah's New Covenant :bAn Augustinian Reading /cJoshua N. Moon. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJournal of Theological Interpretation Supplements ;v300tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgments -- tI. Introduction -- tII. Jeremiah's New Covenant in Jerome and Augustine -- tIII. Jeremiah's New Covenant in High Medieval Theology -- tIV. The Early Modern Reformed Tradition -- tV. 17th Century Reformed: The Continued Struggle -- tVI. The New Covenant in Modern Discourse -- tVII. The Context of the New Covenant -- tVIII. Jeremiah's New Covenant: Restitutio ad Integrum -- tIX. Conclusions and Theological Directions -- tWorks Cited -- tIndexes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe struggle to read Jeremiah 31:31-34 as Christian Scripture has a long and divided history, cutting across nearly every major locus of Christian theology. Yet little has been done either to examine closely the varieties of interpretation in the Christian tradition from the post-Nicene period to the modern era, or to make use of such interpretations as helpful interlocutors. This work begins with Augustine's interpretation of Jer 31:31-34 as an absolute contrast between unbelief and faith, rather than the now-standard reading (found in Jerome) of a contrast between two successive religio-historical eras-one that governed Israel (the "old covenant") and a new era and its covenant inaugurated in the coming of Christ. Augustine's absolute contrast loosened the strict temporal concern, so that the faithful of any era were members of the "new covenant." The study traces Augustine's reading of an absolute contrast in a few key moments of Christian interpretation: Thomas Aquinas and high medieval theology, then the 16th and 17th century Reformed tradition. The thesis aims at a constructive reading of Jer 31:31-34, and so the struggle identified in these moments in the Christian tradition is brought into dialogue with modern critical discussions from Bernhard Duhm to the present. Finally, the author turns to an exegetical argument for an 'Augustinian' reading of the contrast of the covenants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781575066417zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781575066417423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781575066417/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK